        marks: 9, tier: 'red',
        modelAnswer: `Why simplification matters:\n• Fewer gates reduce propagation delay, lowering the critical path and allowing a higher clock speed.\n• Fewer gates reduce silicon area, cost and power consumption.\n• Simpler circuits are easier to verify, test and reason about — reducing design bugs.\n• Reduction is a recurring task in CPU design, where millions of instances of a small circuit are replicated.\nBoolean algebra simplification:\n• F = (A AND B) OR (A AND NOT B) OR (NOT A AND B).\n• Apply distributive law on the first two terms: (A AND B) OR (A AND NOT B) = A AND (B OR NOT B) = A AND 1 = A.\n• So F = A OR (NOT A AND B).\n• Apply the absorption-type identity: A OR (NOT A AND B) = A OR B (expand: (A OR NOT A) AND (A OR B) = 1 AND (A OR B) = A OR B).\n• Simplified: F = A OR B — two inputs, a single OR gate.\nKarnaugh map approach:\n• Draw a 2-variable K-map with A across and B down (or similar). Place a 1 in each cell corresponding to AB, A NOT B and NOT A B, and 0 in the NOT A NOT B cell.\n• The three 1s can be grouped as two pairs: a horizontal pair covering A-column (covers AB and A NOT B → implicant A) and a vertical pair covering B-row (covers AB and NOT A B → implicant B).\n• OR the implicants: F = A OR B — the same minimal form.\nEvaluation:\n• Boolean algebra is general and works for any number of variables but requires skill with identities (De Morgan\'s, distributive, absorption) and can be error-prone.\n• Karnaugh maps are visual and systematic for up to 4–5 variables, always yielding a minimal sum-of-products by grouping adjacent 1s in powers of two; they become unwieldy for many variables.\n• For large circuits, industry uses Quine-McCluskey or heuristic tools (e.g. Espresso) inside synthesis software — but the underlying theory is Boolean algebra applied algorithmically.\n• The worked example demonstrates both techniques converging on the same minimal circuit — a single OR gate — a 67% gate-count reduction from the original three AND gates plus two ORs.`
